  "source": {
    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine",
    "content": "In patients with suspected or confirmed aortic dissection, immediate control of blood pressure and heart rate is essential to limit propagation of the dissection. The goal is to reduce the force of left ventricular ejection (dP/dt), which is determined by both blood pressure and heart rate. The initial drug of choice is an intravenous beta blocker (e.g., metoprolol, esmolol, or labetalol, which also has alpha-blocking properties) to reduce heart rate to approximately 60 beats per minute. If systolic blood pressure remains >120 mmHg after adequate beta blockade, a vasodilator such as intravenous nitroprusside should be added. Vasodilators should never be used without prior beta blockade because they can increase the force of left ventricular ejection by causing reflex tachycardia, potentially worsening the dissection."
