  "source": {
    "file_name": "American Journal of Respiratory and Critical Care Medicine",
    "content": "Initial management of massive hemoptysis should focus on airway protection, lateralization of the patient with the bleeding lung in the dependent position to prevent aspiration into the non-bleeding lung, oxygen supplementation, and establishment of intravenous access. Bronchoscopy plays a crucial role in localizing the bleeding site and implementing temporary hemostatic measures such as cold saline lavage, epinephrine instillation, or balloon tamponade. Rigid bronchoscopy may be preferred in cases of massive bleeding due to its superior airway control and suctioning capabilities. Bronchial artery embolization is the procedure of choice for controlling bleeding, with success rates of 85-95%. Surgical resection is considered when bleeding cannot be controlled by less invasive methods or for specific conditions like aspergilloma."
