    "file_name": "European Society of Cardiology Guidelines for the Management of Valvular Heart Disease",
    "content": "In pregnant women with moderate to severe mitral stenosis (valve area <1.5cm²) who are symptomatic (NYHA functional class II-IV) or have pulmonary artery pressure >50 mmHg despite optimal medical therapy, percutaneous mitral commissurotomy (PMC) should be considered, preferably after 20 weeks of gestation. PMC is recommended in symptomatic patients with significant mitral stenosis who are not at high risk for procedural complications. In patients with severe mitral stenosis planning pregnancy, if they are symptomatic or if pulmonary systolic pressure is >50 mmHg, intervention (usually PMC) should be performed before pregnancy. Termination of pregnancy should be discussed in severe mitral stenosis with NYHA class III/IV symptoms and/or estimated systolic pulmonary artery pressure >50 mmHg despite medical therapy, where PMC is not feasible or has failed. Hemoptysis in mitral stenosis is usually due to pulmonary venous hypertension leading to rupture of bronchial venous anastomoses or alveolar capillaries, and can be a sign of decompensation requiring urgent intervention."
